\begin_layout Section*
Problem 1: Irreps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D(n)D(n')=D(n+n')$
\end_inset

, it follows as in class that 
\begin_inset Formula $D(n)=e^{-isn}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 (In particular, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $D(n)=D(1)^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(1)\neq0$
\end_inset

.) Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D(N)=1$
\end_inset

 (rotation by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{N}^{N}$
\end_inset

), it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\frac{2\pi}{N}k$
\end_inset

 for some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 we have the 1d irreps
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{(k)}(n)=e^{-\frac{2\pi i}{N}kn}.
\]

\end_inset

Furthermore, since we have 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 rotations in the 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{N}$
\end_inset

 group, all in their own conjugacy class, it must be that we have exactly
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 irreps.
 This is true because 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D^{(k+N)}(n)=e^{-\frac{2\pi i}{N}kn-2\pi ni}=D^{(k)}(n),
\]

\end_inset

i.e.
 only 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0,1,\ldots,N-1$
\end_inset

 are distinct irreps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Similar to class and in homework, a partner function of 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 is of the of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{\ell}=\phi_{0}e^{\frac{2\pi i}{N}k\ell}
\]

\end_inset

for any constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ell-n}=D^{(k)}(n)\phi_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 (Note that this is periodic: 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ell+N}=\phi_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.) Since all of the eigenvectors can be chosen in the form of partner functions,
 these are our eigenvectors.
 We an just plug them in to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Theta}\phi$
\end_inset

 to find the eigenvalues.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

-th of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Theta}\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\kappa}{m}\left(2\phi_{\ell}-\phi_{\ell+1}-\phi_{\ell-1}\right)=\frac{\kappa}{m}\left(2-e^{\frac{2\pi i}{N}k}-e^{-\frac{2\pi i}{N}k}\right)\phi_{0}e^{\frac{2\pi i}{N}k\ell}=\frac{2\kappa}{m}\left(1-\cos(2\pi k/N)\right)\phi_{\ell},
\]

\end_inset

confirming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{k}^{2}=\frac{2\kappa}{m}\left(1-\cos(2\pi k/N)\right)=\frac{2\kappa}{m}\sin^{2}\left(\frac{\pi k}{N}\right)=\omega_{k+N}^{2}=\omega_{-k}^{2}=\omega_{N-k}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0,1,\ldots,N-1$
\end_inset

.
 (Note that we have exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 linearly independent eigenvectors for our 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 Note also that the eigenvalues are real and nonnegative, which must be
 true for a real-symmetric positive-semidefinite matrix.) Hence the eigenfrequenc
ies are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{k}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{2\kappa}{m}}\sin\left(\frac{\pi k}{N}\right).
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For odd 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, we also have the mirror symmetries 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
There are 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 mirror-symmetry planes, one through each vertex (bisecting the opposite
 edge).
 (Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 were even, we would have 
\begin_inset Formula $N/2$
\end_inset

 mirror planes through vertices and 
\begin_inset Formula $N/2$
\end_inset

 mirror planes through edges.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{N}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is conjugate to 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{N}^{-n}$
\end_inset

 under a mirror flip.
 Ever mirror plane is conjugate to every other mirror plane under a rotation.
 Hence there are the following conjugacy classes: 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{N}^{0}=E$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{N-1}{2}$
\end_inset

 pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{N}^{\pm n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,\ldots\frac{N-1}{2}$
\end_inset

, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\sigma$
\end_inset

 conjugacy class of mirror planes.
 (Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 were even, the mirror planes through vertices and faces would be in different
 conjugacy classes.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There are 
\begin_inset Formula $1+\frac{N-1}{2}+1=\frac{N+3}{2}$
\end_inset

 conjugacy classes, and hence 
\series bold
there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{N+3}{2}$
\end_inset

 irreps
\series default
.
 The sum of their 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dimensions}^{2}$
\end_inset

 must equal the number of elements in the group, 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

.
 A further hint comes from the 2-fold degeneracies of the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{k}^{2}=\omega_{N-k}^{2}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

, which lets us know to expect 2-dimensional irreps.
 If you count how many 2d irreps you can half, it turns out that you must
 have 
\series bold
2 1d irreps and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{N-1}{2}$
\end_inset

 2d irreps.

\series default
 This gives a sum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{dimensions}^{2}$
\end_inset

 equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1+1+2^{2}\frac{N-1}{2}=2+2N-2=2N$
\end_inset

, which is the correct sum.
 Indeed, the degenerate eigenvalues above for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ne0$
\end_inset

 correspond to partners of 2d irreps (while 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 is the trivial 1d irrep).
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In fact, this is precisely the 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{N\text{v}}$
\end_inset

 group .
 In pset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

2 you analyzed 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{3\text{v}}$
\end_inset

 and you found that it had two 1d irreps and 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\frac{3-1}{2}$
\end_inset

 2d irreps, exactly consistent with the general result here.
 (In the fall 2005 midterm there was an example of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{5\text{v}}$
\end_inset

, which had two 1d irreps and 
\begin_inset Formula $2=\frac{5-1}{2}$
\end_inset

 2d irreps, again consistent with our result here.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

One thing that you may find surprising is that there are 
\emph on
two
\emph default
 1d irreps, but we only have 
\emph on
one
\emph default
 nondegenerate eigenvalue above at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Why is this? The key thing is to understand what a mirror plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 through a vertex 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 does to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ell}$
\end_inset

 represents a displacement going 
\emph on
around
\emph default
 the circle tangentially, a mirror flip through 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 must send 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ell}\to-\phi_{\ell}$
\end_inset

.
 That means the zero-frequency eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ell}=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
cannot
\emph default
 transform as the trivial representation 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Instead, it must transform as the 
\emph on
other
\emph default
 1d irrep, in which 
\begin_inset Formula $D(n)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\sigma)=-1$
\end_inset

 .
 To get the trivial irrep, we would actually have to consider a 
\emph on
different physical problem
\emph default
 with the same symmetry group, for example oscillations in the 
\emph on
radial
\emph default
 direction from a ring of masses.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section*
Problem 2: Index guiding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In class and in homework, you considered the problem of index-guiding: localizat
ion in a higher-index region with translational symmetry.
 In this problem, you should do the same thing but with a different wave
 equation, the Schrödinger equation, whose eigenmode equation for time-harmonic
 modes 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\vec{x})e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{H}\psi=\underbrace{\left(-\nabla^{2}+V\right)}_{\hat{H}}\psi=\omega\psi
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 function.
 In particular, we consider an 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-independent potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(y)$
\end_inset

 in 2d, as depicted in figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:potential"

\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $|y|>h$
\end_inset

 and is otherwise negative 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

on average,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}V(y)\,dy<0$
\end_inset

.
 You are also given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}|V|\,dy$
\end_inset

 is finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}$
\end_inset

 is Hermitian under the usual inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\phi,\psi\rangle=\int\phi^{*}\psi$
\end_inset

 for functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi,\psi$
\end_inset

 that decay sufficiently rapidly, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\psi,\hat{H}\psi\rangle=\int(|\nabla\psi|^{2}+V|\psi|^{2})$
\end_inset

 via integration by parts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{k}(y)e^{ikx}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reduced
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 eigenproblem 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{k}\psi_{k}=\omega(k)\psi_{k}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}=-\frac{d^{2}}{dy^{2}}+k^{2}+V(y)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 dependence is purely in the form of an additive constant 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{2}$
\end_inset

, so it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(k)=\omega(0)+k^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Furthermore, similar to the Maxwell case from class, we expect that the
 eigenvalues will be divided into the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

light cone
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 — a continuous range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 corresponding solutions in the infinite 
\begin_inset Formula $V=0$
\end_inset

 regions — and one or more discrete guided modes pulled down below the light
 cone by the 
\begin_inset Formula $V<0$
\end_inset

 region.
 The light cone, the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $V=0$
\end_inset

, is just planewaves 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i(kx+k_{y}y)}$
\end_inset

 for all real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{y}$
\end_inset

, with eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=k^{2}+k_{y}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This gives the light cone as a continuous region 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\ge k^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

As we will show explicitly in the next part, there is at least one guided
 mode below the light cone.
 There could be more than one if the 
\begin_inset Formula $V<0$
\end_inset

 region is big/deep enough, but in any case there will be a finite number.
 Unlike the Maxwell case, however, we will 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 get more more higher-order modes as we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, because of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(k)=\omega(0)+k^{2}$
\end_inset

 property from above: whatever guided modes we have will maintain a fixed
 separation from the light cone.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

